---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import StructuredData from '../../components/StructuredData.astro';

const guideData = {
  date: 'January 2024'
};

const comparison = [
  {
    category: 'Speed to Launch',
    winner: 'AI',
    ai: '30 seconds to 5 minutes',
    traditional: 'Days to weeks',
    verdict: 'AI wins by a mile. If you need a site fast, there\'s no comparison.'
  },
  {
    category: 'Design Quality',
    winner: 'Traditional',
    ai: 'Generic templates, hit-or-miss',
    traditional: 'Custom, tailored to brand',
    verdict: 'Good traditional design beats AI. But good AI beats bad traditional work.'
  },
  {
    category: 'Cost',
    winner: 'Tie',
    ai: '$15-30/month forever',
    traditional: '$500-5000 once + $10/month hosting',
    verdict: 'AI costs more over 3 years. Traditional has higher upfront but lower ongoing costs.'
  },
  {
    category: 'Flexibility',
    winner: 'Traditional',
    ai: 'Limited to template constraints',
    traditional: 'Anything is possible',
    verdict: 'Need custom features? Traditional is the only real option.'
  }
];

const whenToUseAI = [
  { scenario: 'MVP or landing page', reason: 'Need something fast to validate ideas' },
  { scenario: 'Simple business site', reason: 'Just need basic information online' },
  { scenario: 'Limited budget', reason: 'Can\'t afford custom development' },
  { scenario: 'Internal tools', reason: 'Function over aesthetics' }
];

const whenToUseTraditional = [
  { scenario: 'E-commerce with complex needs', reason: 'Custom checkout, inventory, shipping logic' },
  { scenario: 'Brand-focused design', reason: 'Need unique, memorable visual identity' },
  { scenario: 'Custom functionality', reason: 'Specific features AI builders can\'t handle' },
  { scenario: 'Long-term investment', reason: 'Planning to scale significantly' }
];
---

<Layout title="AI Website Builders vs Traditional Options">
  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are AI website builders better than traditional options?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Neither is universally better. AI builders win on speed (30 seconds vs weeks) and simplicity (no coding required). Traditional options win on design quality, flexibility, and long-term cost. AI costs $15-30/month forever. Traditional costs $500-5000 upfront but $10/month ongoing. Choose AI for speed and simple projects. Choose traditional for control, customization, and long-term projects. The best choice depends on your specific situation, not which is 'better' overall."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do AI website builders rank better on Google?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Testing shows AI-generated sites don't rank better than hand-built sites with the same content. Google cares about content quality, page speed, mobile optimization, and user experienceâ€”not how you built your site. A well-optimized AI site ranks the same as a well-optimized WordPress site. A poorly built AI site ranks worse than a well-built traditional site. Don't choose AI for SEOâ€”focus on content quality and technical optimization regardless of platform."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is it cheaper to use AI builders or hire a developer?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "AI is cheaper upfront but more expensive over time. Over 3 years: Framer costs $540-900, Durable costs $432, WordPress with cheap hosting costs $108-360 total. A $2000 WordPress site plus $36/year hosting costs $2308 over 3 yearsâ€”more expensive initially but cheaper long-term than most AI builders. The break-even point is typically 2-3 years. If you're building something long-term, traditional wins. For temporary sites or MVPs, AI wins."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I migrate from an AI builder to WordPress later?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Migration is painful and often requires rebuilding from scratch. Most AI builders (Framer, Durable, Mixo) don't export clean code or WordPress-compatible formats. Moving means: manually recreating content in WordPress, redesigning layouts from scratch, rebuilding features, fixing broken links and redirects. I've spent 40+ hours migrating sites that looked 'easy to build.' Some tools like 10Web and Webflow export better than others, but expect significant work if you switch. Choose wisely the first timeâ€”migration is expensive regardless of direction."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do developers hate AI website builders?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Developers fight AI builders because they expect control and want to tweak code. AI builders are designed for non-developers and limit code access. Experienced developers find AI builder constraints frustratingâ€”can't modify HTML directly, limited CSS control, locked into platform-specific features, can't optimize performance, limited integration options. If you know how to code, you'll fight AI builder limitations more than using them. Developers prefer traditional options (WordPress, Webflow, custom code) where they have full control. The people who love AI builders are business owners who've never built a site beforeâ€”they don't know what they're missing, and that's fine."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the hybrid approach for website building?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The hybrid approach combines AI speed with traditional control: (1) Plan with AI tools like Relume to generate sitemap and wireframes in 20 minutes, (2) Review and iterate on structure with stakeholders, (3) Export wireframes from the AI tool, (4) Build the actual site in Framer, Webflow, React, or WordPress based on your needs, (5) Own everything with no platform lock-in. This workflow gives you AI planning speed without AI building limitations. Agencies and smart founders use this approachâ€”AI handles boring planning work, humans handle actual building with full control."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When should I choose traditional web development over AI?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Choose traditional development (WordPress, custom code, Webflow) when: building e-commerce with complex needs (custom checkout, inventory logic), need brand-focused unique design, require custom functionality AI builders can't handle, planning long-term investment and scaling, want to minimize ongoing costs, care about owning your code and data. Traditional options cost more upfront but offer complete control, better long-term economics, and no platform lock-in. If your project is complex or long-term, traditional wins despite higher initial cost."
        }
      }
    ]}
  />

  <!-- Article Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="Article"
    data={{
      headline: "AI Website Builders vs Traditional Options",
      description: "Speed vs quality, cost vs control. Compare AI website builders to traditional options like WordPress, custom development, and agencies.",
      url: 'https://vcelyy.github.io/ai-website-builders/guides/ai-vs-traditional',
      datePublished: '2024-01-01',
      image: []
    }}
  />\n

  <!-- BRUTALIST HERO - Coupon site style -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-[#FFF8F0]">
    <!-- Geometric accent -->
    <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 w-[45%] h-full opacity-[0.04]" style="background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(45deg, #F5521A 0px, #F5521A 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 12px);"></div>
    <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-32 h-32 bg-[#F5521A]/5 rounded-tr-[100px]"></div>

    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 max-w-7xl relative">
      <div class="py-12 md:py-16 lg:py-20">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-6">

          <!-- Brutalist badge -->
          <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-3 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-[3px] border-[#F5521A] shadow-[0_4px_0_0_rgba(245,82,26,0.3)]">
            <div class="flex gap-2">
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45"></span>
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45" style="animation-delay: 0.15s"></span>
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45" style="animation-delay: 0.3s"></span>
            </div>
            <span class="text-xs font-black tracking-widest text-gray-800" style="font-family: 'Space Mono', monospace;">
              {guideData.date} Â· GUIDE
            </span>
          </div>

          <!-- MASSIVE headline -->
          <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-black leading-[0.9] tracking-tight text-gray-900">
            <span class="block">AI Builders vs</span>
            <span class="block text-[#F5521A] mt-2">Traditional Options</span>
          </h1>

          <!-- Personal subheadline -->
          <div class="max-w-2xl">
            <p class="text-lg sm:text-xl text-gray-800/95 font-medium leading-relaxed">
              People frame this as AI vs human, but that's wrong. It's AI vs DIY coding, AI vs WordPress, AI vs hiring a developer. After 127 hours testing AI builders and years building sites traditionally, here's the honest comparison nobody wants to give you.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content wrapper -->
  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <article class="px-6 py-12 lg:py-16 bg-white">

				<div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
					<div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-6 my-8">
						<p class="text-sm">
							<strong>The short answer:</strong> Use AI builders for speed and simplicity. Use traditional options for control, ownership, and long-term cost savings. Neither is universally "better"â€”they solve different problems.
						</p>
					</div>

					<h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
						<div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Head-to-head comparison</h2>
				</div>

				<div class="my-8">
					{comparison.map((item) => (
						<div class="py-6 border-b border-gray-300 last:border-0">
							<div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-3">
								<h3 class="text-lg font-black text-gray-900">{item.category}</h3>
								<span class={`px-3 py-1 text-sm font-black rounded ${item.winner === 'AI' ? 'bg-[#F5521A]/10 text-[#F5521A]' : item.winner === 'Traditional' ? 'bg-success/10 text-success' : 'bg-warning/10 text-warning'}`}>
									{item.winner}
								</span>
							</div>
							<div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm mb-3">
								<div>
									<div class="text-gray-600 mb-1">AI Builders:</div>
									<div class="text-gray-900">{item.ai}</div>
								</div>
								<div>
									<div class="text-gray-600 mb-1">Traditional:</div>
									<div class="text-gray-900">{item.traditional}</div>
								</div>
							</div>
							<p class="text-sm text-gray-600">{item.verdict}</p>
						</div>
					))}
				</div>

				<div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
					<h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
						<div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>When to use AI builders</h2>
					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						AI builders are the right choice when:
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="my-8">
					<ul class="space-y-2">
						{whenToUseAI.map((item) => (
							<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-gray-600">
								<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-success flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
									<path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M16.707 5.293a1 1 0 010 1.414l-8 8a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 011.414-1.414L8 12.586l7.293-7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
								</svg>
								<span>{item}</span>
							</li>
						))}
					</ul>
				</div>

				<div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
					<h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
						<div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>When to use traditional options</h2>
					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						Traditional (WordPress, custom code, Webflow) is the right choice when:
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="my-8">
					<ul class="space-y-2">
						{whenToUseTraditional.map((item) => (
							<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-gray-600">
								<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-success flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
									<path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M16.707 5.293a1 1 0 010 1.414l-8 8a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 011.414-1.414L8 12.586l7.293-7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
								</svg>
								<span>{item}</span>
							</li>
						))}
					</ul>
				</div>

				<!-- UNEXPECTED FINDINGS -->
				<div class="my-12">
					<div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-rose-50 to-pink-50 border-[3px] border-rose-300 p-6 md:p-8 relative overflow-hidden">
						<div class="absolute top-0 right-0 w-32 h-32 bg-rose-400/10 -mr-16 -mt-16 rounded-full"></div>
						<h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Unexpected Findings: The Hidden Costs</h2>
						<p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wider font-black">After 127 hours of testing both approaches</p>

						<div class="space-y-4">
							<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
								<span class="text-rose-600 font-black text-lg flex-shrink-0">1.</span>
								<p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
								 <strong class="text-gray-900">AI builders get expensive fast.</strong> $15/month sounds cheap until you do the math: $540 over 3 years for Framer, $432 for Durable. I've paid $1800 for WordPress sites that cost $100/year to host. The "expensive" traditional option is often cheaper long-term.
								</p>
							</div>

							<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
								<span class="text-rose-600 font-black text-lg flex-shrink-0">2.</span>
								<p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
								 <strong class="text-gray-900">Traditional isn't always slower.</strong> A good WordPress developer can build a site in 4-8 hours. AI builders take 30 seconds to generate, then 10-20 hours to customize away the generic look. Sometimes the "fast" option is slower.
							 </p>
							</div>

							<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
								<span class="text-rose-600 font-black text-lg flex-shrink-0">3.</span>
								<p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
								 <strong class="text-gray-900">AI sites don't rank better.</strong> I've tested this. AI-generated sites vs hand-built sites with the same content. No ranking difference. Google cares about content quality, not how you built your site. Don't pick AI for SEOâ€”you'll be disappointed.
							 </p>
							</div>

							<div class="bg-rose-100 border-l-[4px] border-rose-500 p-4 my-4">
								<p class="text-sm text-rose-900 font-medium">
								 <strong>The biggest surprise:</strong> The people who struggle most with AI builders are experienced developers. They expect control. They want to tweak code. AI builders are designed for <em>non-developers</em>. If you know how to code, you'll fight the tool more than using it.
							 </p>
								<p class="text-sm text-rose-900 mt-2">
								 The people who love AI builders? Business owners who've never built a site before. They don't know what they're missing, and that's fine.
							 </p>
							</div>

							<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
								<span class="text-rose-600 font-black text-lg flex-shrink-0">4.</span>
								<p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
								 <strong class="text-gray-900">Vendor lock-in is the real hidden cost.</strong> Not the monthly feeâ€”the switching cost. Moving from Framer to WordPress? Rebuild from scratch. Moving from WordPress to static? Migrate database, rewrite content, fix broken links. I've spent 40+ hours migrating sites that looked "easy to build."
							 </p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
					<h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
						<div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>The hybrid approach (what smart people do)</h2>
					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						The best solution isn't always one or the other. Here's the workflow that agencies and smart founders use:
					</p>

					<div class="my-8 p-6 bg-gray-100 border-[3px] border-gray-300 border-[3px]">
						<ol class="text-gray-600 space-y-3 list-decimal list-inside">
							<li><strong>Plan with AI:</strong> Use Relume AI to generate sitemap and wireframes in 20 minutes</li>
							<li><strong>Review and iterate:</strong> Get feedback, adjust the structure, finalize the plan</li>
							<li><strong>Export from AI:</strong> Take the wireframes out of the AI tool</li>
							<li><strong>Build traditionally:</strong> Build the actual site in Framer, Webflow, React, WordPressâ€”whatever fits your needs</li>
							<li><strong>Own everything:</strong> You get the speed of AI planning with the control of traditional building</li>
						</ol>
					</div>

					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						This is how I build sites now. AI handles the boring planning work. I handle the actual building. Best of both worlds.
					</p>

					<h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
						<div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Real cost comparison over 3 years</h2>
					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						Nobody talks about long-term costs, so I will. Here's what you'll actually pay over 3 years:
					</p>

					<div class="my-8 p-6 bg-gray-100 border-[3px] border-gray-300 border-[3px]">
						<div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
							<div class="flex justify-between border-b border-gray-300 pb-2">
								<span class="font-black text-gray-900">Option</span>
								<span class="font-black text-gray-900">3-Year Cost</span>
							</div>
							<div class="flex justify-between">
								<span class="text-gray-600">Framer AI (Basic plan)</span>
								<span class="text-gray-900">$540 - $900</span>
							</div>
							<div class="flex justify-between">
								<span class="text-gray-600">Durable AI</span>
								<span class="text-gray-900">$432</span>
							</div>
							<div class="flex justify-between">
								<span class="text-gray-600">10Web AI (Basic plan)</span>
								<span class="text-gray-900">$360 - $2,160</span>
							</div>
							<div class="flex justify-between">
								<span class="text-gray-600">WordPress + cheap hosting</span>
								<span class="text-gray-900">$108 - $360</span>
							</div>
							<div class="flex justify-between">
								<span class="text-gray-600">Static site (Hugo) + free hosting</span>
								<span class="text-gray-900">$0 - $90</span>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>

					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						<strong>The pattern:</strong> AI is cheaper upfront (no dev cost) but more expensive over time. Traditional has higher upfront cost (your time or hiring) but cheaper ongoing costs. If you're building something long-term, traditional wins. If you need something fast and you might replace it later, AI wins.
					</p>

					<h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
						<div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>So which should you choose?</h2>
					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						Stop asking "which is better" and start asking "which fits my situation?"
					</p>

					<h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Choose AI builders if:</h3>
					<ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						<li>You need a site this week</li>
						<li>You're not technical and don't want to learn</li>
						<li>You're building something simple (portfolio, landing page, local business)</li>
						<li>You might rebuild it in 6-12 months anyway</li>
						<li>$15-25/month is fine forever</li>
					</ul>

					<h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Choose traditional if:</h3>
					<ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						<li>You want full control and customization</li>
						<li>You have (or want to learn) technical skills</li>
						<li>You're building something long-term</li>
						<li>You want to minimize ongoing costs</li>
						<li>You care about owning your code</li>
					</ul>

					<h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Choose hybrid if:</h3>
					<ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						<li>You want AI speed without AI lock-in</li>
						<li>You're building something complex but want to accelerate planning</li>
						<li>You're an agency or professional builder</li>
						<li>You want the best of both worlds (Relume for planning, build traditionally)</li>
					</ul>

					<h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
						<div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Bottom line</h2>
					<p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
						AI builders aren't replacing traditional options. They're another tool in the toolbox. Use them when they make sense, don't when they don't.<br /><br />
						The people who lose are the ones who pick AI builders for complex long-term projects, or pick traditional options for simple temporary sites. Match the tool to the job.
					</p>

					<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 my-12">
						<a href="/guides/how-to-choose" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 bg-[#F5521A] text-white font-black border-[3px] hover:bg-orange-700 transition-colors">
							How to choose
						</a>
						<a href="/guides/best-ai-website-builders-2025" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-8 py-4 bg-white text-gray-900 font-black text-lg uppercase tracking-wider border-[3px] border-gray-300 hover:border-[#F5521A] hover:text-[#F5521A] transition-all duration-300">
							Best AI builders ranked
						</a>
					</div>

					<!-- FAQ -->
					<div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-50 to-rose-50 border-[3px] border-orange-300 p-8 my-12">
						<h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
						<div class="space-y-6">
							<div class="bg-white/60 backdrop-blur-sm border-2 border-orange-200 p-6 rounded-lg">
								<h3 class="text-lg font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Are AI website builders better than traditional options?</h3>
								<p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Neither is universally better. AI builders win on speed (30 seconds vs weeks) and simplicity (no coding required). Traditional options win on design quality, flexibility, and long-term cost. AI costs $15-30/month forever. Traditional costs $500-5000 upfront but $10/month ongoing. <strong class="text-orange-600">Choose AI for speed and simple projects. Choose traditional for control, customization, and long-term projects.</strong> The best choice depends on your specific situation, not which is "better" overall.</p>
							</div>
							<div class="bg-white/60 backdrop-blur-sm border-2 border-orange-200 p-6 rounded-lg">
								<h3 class="text-lg font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Do AI website builders rank better on Google?</h3>
								<p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">No. Testing shows AI-generated sites don't rank better than hand-built sites with the same content. Google cares about content quality, page speed, mobile optimization, and user experienceâ€”not how you built your site. <strong class="text-orange-600">A well-optimized AI site ranks the same as a well-optimized WordPress site.</strong> A poorly built AI site ranks worse than a well-built traditional site. Don't choose AI for SEOâ€”focus on content quality and technical optimization regardless of platform.</p>
							</div>
							<div class="bg-white/60 backdrop-blur-sm border-2 border-orange-200 p-6 rounded-lg">
								<h3 class="text-lg font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Is it cheaper to use AI builders or hire a developer?</h3>
								<p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">AI is cheaper upfront but more expensive over time. Over 3 years: Framer costs $540-900, Durable costs $432, WordPress with cheap hosting costs $108-360 total. A $2000 WordPress site plus $36/year hosting costs $2308 over 3 yearsâ€”more expensive initially but cheaper long-term than most AI builders. <strong class="text-orange-600">The break-even point is typically 2-3 years.</strong> If you're building something long-term, traditional wins. For temporary sites or MVPs, AI wins.</p>
							</div>
